\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Number Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What is Number Theory?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Number theory is the branch of mathematics primarily concerned with the
 integers and their properties.
 Historically, number theory started with the ancient Greeks (although others
 might reasonably argue otherwise).
 Number theory is sometimes called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

theory of numbers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

higher arithmetic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Here are some examples of questions and concepts considered in number theory:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given two integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, if we add, subtract, and multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, then we get another integer.
 If we divide 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, we usually do not get another integer.
 However, if 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is an integer, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 For a given integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, what are all the divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

? Those integers which have no divisors except 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and itself are called 
\series bold
prime
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Tabular
<lyxtabular version="3" rows="5" columns="2">
<features tabularvalignment="middle">
<column alignment="center" valignment="top">
