<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $31$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $11111$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Euclid, 300 B.C.) There are infinitely prime numbers.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p+2$
\end_inset

 are both prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(p,p+2)$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
twin prime
\series default
 pair.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{conj}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There are infinitely many twin prime pairs.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{conj}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

For 2000+ years, no one knows how to prove or disprove this! However in
 2013, Y.
 Zhang showed that there is a definite number 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 strictly less than 
\begin_inset Formula $70,000,000$
\end_inset

 such that there are infinitely prime pairs which differ by less than or
 equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Subsequent researchers, namely J.
 Maynard, lowered 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to less than 
\begin_inset Formula $600$
\end_inset

.
 And after than the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

polymath
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 group lowered 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $246$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fermat's Last Theorem (FLT)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Motivation: We know that there are integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{2}+b^{2}=c^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, take 
\begin_inset Formula $a=3$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=4$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=5$
\end_inset

.
 In the 1600s, Fermat wondered what happened if we change the exponent to
 integers strictly greater than two.
 He stated there do not exist positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}+b^{n}=c^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

.
 In the 1990s, Andrew Wiles (with the help of Richard Taylor) proved a result
 that implies FLT.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Covention: Unless otherwise stated, we use lowercase letters to denote integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
divides 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, written 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ac=b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The 
\series bold
greatest common divisor 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

, is the greatest integer which divides both 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
least common multiple 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

, is the least integer which is divided by both 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid c$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad=b$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid c$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $be=c$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
c & =be\\
 & =(ad)e\\
 & =a(de).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 So 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid bx+cy$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ad=b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $ae=c$
\end_inset

.
 So
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
bx+cy & =(ad)x+(ae)y\\
 & =a(dx)+a(ey)\\
 & =a(dx+ey).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid bx+cy$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a=\prod_{\mbox{primes}}p_{i}^{e_{i}}\qquad b=\prod_{\mbox{primes}}p_{i}^{f_{i}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a,b)=\prod_{\mbox{primes}}p_{i}^{\mbox{min}(e_{i},f_{i})}\qquad[a,b]=\prod_{\mbox{primes}}p_{i}^{\mbox{max}(e_{i},f_{i})}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Division Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There exists unique integers 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a=bq+r$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le r<|b|$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Consequences of Bezout's Identity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid bc$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid bc$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ak=bc$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
c & =c(ax+by)\\
 & =acx+bcy\\
 & =a(cx+ky).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid c$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid c$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $a\mid c$
\end_inset

, there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ak_{1}=c$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b\mid c$
\end_inset

, there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $bk_{2}=c$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)=1$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
c & =c(ax+by)\\
 & =ab(k_{2}x+k_{1}y).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So 
\begin_inset Formula $ab\mid c$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,c)=1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $(ab,c)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,c)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,c)=1$
\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $x,x',y,y'$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+cy=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $bx'+cy'=1$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1 & =(ax+cy)(bx'+cy')\\
 & =ab(xx')+c(axy'+bx'y+cyy').
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This expresses 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 as a 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

- linear combination of 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $ab$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are relatively prime.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Equivalence Relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 denote sets.
 A 
\series bold
relation 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is a subset of the cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $S\times T$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\series bold
relation on 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is just a relation from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to itself.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $|S|=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|T|=m$
\end_inset

, then there are 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{mn}$
\end_inset

 possible relations from 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The subset 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\leq}\subset\mathbb{N}\times\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\leq}=\{(m,n)\mid m\leq n\}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the usual less than or equals to relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 be a relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
reflexive 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
symmetric 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is 
\series bold
transitive 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\sim z$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim z$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive, then we say 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 is an 
\series bold
equivalence relation
\series default
.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Congruence modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The relation is reflexive.
 We have 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv a\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $a-a=0\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The relation is symmetric.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The relation is transitive.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv b\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\equiv c\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $a-b,b-c\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $a-c=(a-b)+(b-c)\in m\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $a\equiv c\mbox{ mod }m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Recall that an equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim$
\end_inset

 on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 induces a partition of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\bigcup_{i}S_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}\cap S_{j}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\neq j$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence class.
 Thus if 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim y$
\end_inset

.
 Congruence modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 partitions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 equivalence classes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For any positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+2+3+\cdots+n=\frac{n(n+1)}{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (By Induction) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)$
\end_inset

 denote the statement 
\begin_inset Formula $"1+2+3+\cdots+n=\frac{n(n+1)}{2}."$
\end_inset

 The base case 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $"1=\frac{1\cdot(1+1)}{2}."$
\end_inset

 which is clearly true.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is true for some arbitrary positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
1+2+3+\cdots+k=\frac{k(k+1)}{2}.\label{eq:induction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding 
\begin_inset Formula $k+1$
\end_inset

 to both sides of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:induction})
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
1+2+3+\cdots+k+k+1 & =\frac{k(k+1)}{2}+k+1\\
 & =\frac{k(k+1)+2(k+1)}{2}\\
 & =\frac{(k+1)(k+2)}{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The 
\series bold
Fibonacci sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\{f_{n}\}_{n=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 
\series default
is defined recursively by 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=f_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n+1}=f_{n}+f_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{1}+f_{2}+f_{3}+\cdots+f_{n}=f_{n+2}-1.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)$
\end_inset

 denote the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $"f_{1}+f_{2}+f_{3}+\cdots+f_{n}=f_{n+2}-1"$
\end_inset

.
 The base case 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $"f_{1}=f_{3}-1"$
\end_inset

, which is true since 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{3}=2$
\end_inset

.
 For the induction step, we need to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $"P(k)\implies P(k+1)"$
\end_inset

 for some arbitrary positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{1}+f_{2}+f_{3}+\cdots+f_{k}+f_{k+1} & =(f_{k+2}-1)+f_{k+1}\\
 & =f_{k+3}-1.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 For all 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
5^{n}\equiv1+4n\mbox{ mod }16.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{theorem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(n)$
\end_inset

 denote the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $"5^{n}\equiv1+4n\mbox{ mod }16"$
\end_inset

.
 The base case 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)$
\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $"5=1+4"$
\end_inset

, which is true.
 For the induction step, we need to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $"P(k)\implies P(k+1)"$
\end_inset

 for some arbitrary positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
5^{k+1} & \equiv5\cdot5^{k}\mbox{ mod }16\\
 & \equiv5\left(1+4k\right)\mbox{ mod }16\\
 & \equiv5+20k\mbox{ mod }16\\
 & \equiv5+4k\mbox{ mod }16\\
 & \equiv1+4k+4\mbox{ mod }16\\
 & \equiv1+4(k+1)\mbox{ mod }16.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k+1)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arithmetic Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on the positive integers is called an 
\series bold
arithmetic 
\series default
function.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Define
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{k}(n)=\sum_{d\mid n}d^{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The number of positive divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is just 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(n)$
\end_inset

.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(24)=9$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Usually in number theory, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau(n)$
\end_inset

 denotes the coefficient of 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 in the power series expansion of the infinite product 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q\prod_{n=1}^{\infty}(1-q^{n})^{24}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\tau(n)q^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

A positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
highly composite 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(n)>\sigma_{0}(k)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k<n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The sequence of highly composite numbers starts as 
\begin_inset Formula $1,2,4,6,12,24,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{rem}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(n)=\frac{\sigma_{0}(1)+\sigma_{0}(2)+\cdots+\sigma_{0}(n)}{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we graph 
\begin_inset Formula $a(n)$
\end_inset

, we notice that it looks like 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(n)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a(n)=\log(n)+(2\gamma-1)+O\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is prime, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(p^{n})>n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{ex}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Answer: 
\series default
The positive divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1,p^{1},\dots,p^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 There are 
\begin_inset Formula $n+1$
\end_inset

 divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(p^{n})=n+1>n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $n=p_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{e_{k}}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{0}(n)=(e_{1}+1)\cdots(e_{k}+1)$
\end_inset

.
 This is because a divisor of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a choice 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1,\dots,e_{i}\}$
\end_inset

 of an exponent for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leq i\leq k$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 An 
\series bold
arithmetic 
\series default
function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is called 
\series bold
multiplicative 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(nm)=f(n)f(m)$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $(n,m)=1$
\end_inset

, and called 
\series bold
totally (or completely) multiplicative 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula $f(nm)=f(n)f(m)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n,m\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{1}$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(2)\sigma(3)=(1+2)(1+3)=1+3+2+6$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{1}(2)\sigma_{1}(3) & =(1+2)(1+3)\\
 & =1+2+3+6\\
 & =\sigma_{1}(6).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma_{1}(p_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{e_{k}}) & =\sigma_{1}(p_{1}^{e_{1}})\cdots\sigma(p_{k}^{e_{k}})\\
 & =(1+p_{1}^{2}+\cdots+p_{1}^{e_{1}})\cdots(1+p_{k}^{2}+\cdots+p_{k}^{e_{k}})\\
 & =\left(\frac{p_{1}^{e_{1}+1}-1}{p_{1}-1}\right)\cdots\left(\frac{p_{k}^{e_{k}+1}-1}{p_{k}-1}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is an integer strictly greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is either prime or uniquely expressible as a product of primes.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}=\{2,4,6,\dots\}$
\end_inset

 be the set of positive even integers.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $6,10$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $30$
\end_inset

 are primes since 
\begin_inset Formula $3,5\notin\mathbb{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $60=6\cdot10=30\cdot2$
\end_inset

.
 So we do not have unique factorization into a product of primes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}$
\end_inset

.
 Recall that Fermat's Last Theorem states that for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>2$
\end_inset

, there do not exist integers 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,c$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{n}+b^{n}=c^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 A false proof of this came in the 
\begin_inset Formula $1800$
\end_inset

's.
 The reason it was false was because the proof assumed the ring 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[\zeta_{n}]$
\end_inset

 has unique factorization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Euler's Phi-Function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(n):=\#$
\end_inset

 of integers between 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 that are relatively prime to 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 For a prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(p^{n})=p^{n}-p^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 The reason is because the divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{n}$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $kp$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,2,\dots,p^{n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi$
\end_inset

 is multiplicative.
 So 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi(p_{1}^{e_{1}}\cdots p_{k}^{e_{k}})=(p_{1}^{e_{1}}-p_{1}^{e_{1}-1})\cdots(p_{k}^{e_{k}}-p_{k}^{e_{k}-1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be an arithmetic function.
 Then 
\series bold
generating function 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the power series 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a(n)x^{n}.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=1+2\cdot\frac{x}{1!}+(2\cdot2!)\cdot\frac{x^{2}}{2!}+(2\cdot3!)\cdot\frac{x^{3}}{3!}+\cdots=\frac{1+x}{1-x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Represent 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 as the vector
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1\\
2\\
2\cdot2!\\
2\cdot3!\\
\vdots
\end{pmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $d/dx$
\end_inset

 can be represented by the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\begin{pmatrix}0 & 1 & 0 & 0 & \cdots\\
0 & 0 & 1 & 0 & \ddots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & \ddots\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \ddots\\
\vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Polygonal Numbers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{n \choose 0}x^{n}=\frac{1}{1-x}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{n \choose 1}x^{n}=\frac{x}{(1-x)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{n \choose 2}x^{n}=\frac{x}{(1-x)^{3}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}n^{2}x^{n} & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\left({n+1 \choose 2}+{n \choose 2}\right)x^{n}\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{n+1 \choose 2}x^{n}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}{n \choose 2}x^{n}\\
 & =\frac{1}{(1-x)^{3}}+\frac{x}{(1-x)^{3}}\\
 & =\frac{1+x}{(1-x)^{3}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}n^{2}x^{n}=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n^{3}x^{n-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n^{3}x^{n}=x\frac{d}{dx}\frac{1+x}{(1-x)^{3}}=\frac{2x^{2}+4x}{(1-x)^{4}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Vanden Eynden
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

In middle school algebra, we learn to solve linear quations in one variable
 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax=C$
\end_inset

.
 Here we consider linear congruences in one variable: 
\begin_inset Formula $ax\equiv c\mbox{ mod }b$
\end_inset

.
 A solution to this congruence exists if and only if for some 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by=c$
\end_inset

.
 A solution to this equation exists if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $d=(a,b)$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 We can find an 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $ax_{0}+by_{0}=d$
\end_inset

 by using Euclidean's algorithm.
 Then, if 
\begin_inset Formula $d\mid c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $dm=c$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $ax_{0}m+by_{0}m=c$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chinese Remainder Theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Given positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},m_{2},\dots,m_{s}$
\end_inset

 that are relatively prime in pairs.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M=m_{1}m_{2}\cdots m_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 be integers such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{gcd}(a_{i},m_{i})=1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,2,\dots,s$
\end_inset

.
 Then the system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
a_{1}x\equiv b_{1} & \mbox{mod }m_{1}\\
a_{2}x\equiv b_{2} & \mbox{mod }m_{2}\\
\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\vdots & \,\,\,\,\,\,\,\,\vdots\\
a_{s}x\equiv b_{s} & \mbox{mod }m_{s}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
has a simultaneous solution that is unique 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{mod }M$
\end_inset

.
 This is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\mathbb{Z}/m_{1}m_{2}\cdots m_{s}\mathbb{Z})^{\times}\cong(\mathbb{Z}/m_{1}\mathbb{Z})^{\times}\times(\mathbb{Z}/m_{2}\mathbb{Z})^{\times}\cdots\times(\mathbb{Z}/m_{s}\mathbb{Z})^{\times}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From ring theory, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathbb{Z}/m_{1}m_{2}\cdots m_{s}\mathbb{Z})=(\mathbb{Z}/m_{1}\mathbb{Z}\cap m_{2}\mathbb{Z}\cap\cdots\cap m_{s}\mathbb{Z})\cong$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
x\equiv2 & \mbox{mod }3\\
x\equiv3 & \mbox{mod }5\\
x\equiv2 & \mbox{mod }7
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
be a system of solutions.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}=M/m_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}=35,\qquad M_{2}=21,\qquad M_{3}=15,\qquad M=105
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Construct 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=2\cdot M_{1}\cdot[M_{1}]_{m_{1}}^{-1}+3\cdot M_{2}\cdot[M_{2}]_{m_{2}}^{-1}+2\cdot M_{3}\cdot[M_{3}]_{m_{3}}^{-1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $[M_{i}]_{m_{i}}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the reduced representative of the inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{i}\mbox{ mod }m_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{example}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Additive Number Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A 
\series bold
partition 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 of an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda:=(\lambda_{1},\dots,\lambda_{k})$
\end_inset

 of positive integers where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}+\cdots+\lambda_{k}=n$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}\geq\cdots\geq\lambda_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
part 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
length 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and the 
\series bold
weight 
\series default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda|$
\end_inset

, is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\series bold
multiplicity 
\series default
of the part 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{\lambda_{i}}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

, is the number of parts 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n)$
\end_inset

 denote the number of partitions of 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 The partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(n)$
\end_inset

 starts out as 
\begin_inset Formula $1,1,2,3,5,7,11,15,\dots$
\end_inset

.
 This sequence my seem simple, but consider 
\begin_inset Formula $p(200)=3972999029388$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
